{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti (Laws of Manu) 7.58** is the verse that refers to the king's six expedients of foreign policy (known as *ṣaḍguṇya* or *ṣaḍguṇyas* in Sanskrit political theory, comprising peace, war, observance/waiting, marching, duality, and alliance-seeking).[^1]\n\nIt states:\n\n> But with a Brahmana who is distinguished among them all, a wise man, the king should deliberate on the supreme counsel connected with the six political expedients. // Mn_7.58 //\n\nThis verse emphasizes consulting a chief Brahmin minister on these measures but does not enumerate them explicitly. No other verses in Chapter 7 list or detail the *ṣaḍguṇya*.\n\n[^1]: [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-c8856b/)",
